Disposition.DispositionRational: Midwives care for women throughout their pregnancy and for the mother and baby up to 28 days after the birth. In some areas women can self-refer to a midwife, in others referral is through the GP.

TriageLine.ReportText: You need to contact the individual's midwife within 1 hour.
Before you go, I will just check whether I need to give you any further instructions or advice.
DOS call
If there are any new symptoms, or if the condition gets worse, changes or you have any other concerns, call us back.
Remember to take a list of any current medications if you go to the out of hours surgery.
Consider alternating the medication ONLY if the symptoms continue or come back before the next dose is due.
Don't give both together unless recommended to do so by a health care professional.
UNDER 12 WEEKS OLD: A baby under 12 weeks should not be given any medicine unless it has been prescribed or advised by a doctor, nurse, health visitor or pharmacist.
Follow the instructions in the pack. If in doubt ask a pharmacist.
Becoming severely ill WITH new marks, like bruising or bleeding under the skin - DIAL 999.
Becoming limp, floppy, unresponsive or having a fit - DIAL 999.
Don't try to cool down by cold sponging or fanning. Cooling down too quickly can cause shivering, which makes the temperature go up again.
Give them plenty to drink, little and often is best. If breastfeeding, breast milk is best.
Jaundice is common in newborn babies. It is not always serious but should be checked .
Bottle-fed babies should continue to be given their normal, full strength formula to prevent dehydration.
Breast-fed babies should continue to be breast-fed as normal to prevent dehydration.
